Attention' and Judgement' 



stimulus, 1 the least illusion, endowing the object as it does with 
properties which it does not possess on my retina, is sufficient to 
establish that perception is a judgement. 2 As I have two eyes, I 
ought to see the object double, and if I see only one of it, that is 
because I construct by means of two images the idea of one object a 
distance away. 3 Perception becomes an interpretation' of the signs 
that our senses provide in accordance with the bodily stimuli? a 
'hypothesis' that the mind evolves to 'explain its impressions to 
itself. 5 But judgement also, brought in to explain the excess of per- 
ception over the retinal impressions, instead of being the act of 
perception itself grasped from within by authentic reflection, 
becomes once more a mere 'factor' of perception, responsible for 
providing what the body does not provide — instead of being a 
transcendental activity, it becomes simply a logical activity of 
drawing a conclusion. 6 In this way we are drawn away from reflection, 

