which all the world's obscurities are elucidated. It is clear, however, that we are 
faced with a dilemma: either the constitution makes the world transparent, in 
which case it is not obvious why reflection needs to pass through the world of 
experience, or else it retains something of that world, and never rids it of its 
opacity. HusserFs thought moves increasingly in this second direction, despite 
many throwbacks to the logicist period — as is seen when he makes a problem of 
